tting-started","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started#why-byte-helpers-exist","content":"UUIDs, ULIDs, TypeIDs, KSUIDs, ObjectIDs, XIDs, and TSIDs have a canonical binary representation. Their `toBytes()` and `fromBytes()` helpers let you store and transport that representation without inventing a second codec."},"169":{"id":"/docs/getting-started-57","page_id":"/docs/getting-started","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started#why-byte-helpers-exist","content":"This matters when an ID lives in a binary database column, a compact protocol payload, or a cache key. A UUID, for instance, is 16 bytes instead of its 36-character string form. The helpers also make the string boundary explicit: convert when data leaves your application, preserve bytes where the system already handles bytes."},"170":{"id":"/docs/getting-started-58","page_id":"/docs/getting-started","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started#why-byte-helpers-exist","content":"String-native formats do not pretend otherwise. Nanoid and CUID v2 have no canonical byte encoding, so they expose a smaller API."},"171":{"id":"/docs/getting-started-59","page_id":"/docs/getting-started","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started#write-into-a-caller-owned-buffer","content":"Binary formats can also write directly into a buffer when an integration already owns the allocation:"},"172":{"id":"/docs/getting-started-60","page_id":"/docs/getting-started","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started#write-into-a-caller-owned-buffer","content":"Public inputs are validated. Explicit random bytes and buffer offsets make tests and boundary integrations deterministic without changing the generator's default monotonic state."},"173":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","page_id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id","type":"page","content":"Choosing an ID","breadcrumbs":["Docs","Guides"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id"},"174":{"id":"/docs/guides/choosing-an-id-0","page_id":"/do