an import change first. Keep the stored identifier format stable, then move generation behind the new direct entry point. Every example below shows the value returned by the uniku generator."],[243,"Minified + gzipped"],[194,"MongoDB `_id` compatibility"],[380,"MongoDB-compatible 12-byte identifiers."],[369,"Most generator modules re-export all four classes, so you rarely need to import from `uniku/errors` directly. Nanoid and CUID v2, which have no binary codec, only re-export `InvalidInputError` and `UniqueIdError`."],[120,"Most generators follow the same pattern: call the generator, keep its primary value, and validate unknown input at the boundary."],[313,"Move CUID v2 to the versioned entry point"],[8,"nanoid"],[147,"Nanoid"],[189,"Nanoid"],[234,"Nanoid"],[375,"Nanoid"],[236,"Nanoid (10 chars)"],[377,"Nanoid is the compact choice for short URLs, invite codes, and session tokens. Its default alphabet is URL-safe; pass a length or options only when the boundary needs a different shape."],[200,"Native `BIGINT` storage"],[107,"No output, exit code only (`0` valid, `2` invalid)"],[88,"Node ID (`0` to `2^node-bits - 1`)"],[193,"Non-sequential, secure identifier."],[321,"Non-sequential, string-native identifiers that resist enumeration."],[237,"npm is 1.1× faster"],[239,"npm is 1.1× faster"],[26,"Number of IDs to generate (default: `1`)"],[11,"objectid"],[155,"ObjectID"],[195,"ObjectID"],[228,"ObjectID"],[379,"ObjectID"],[381,"ObjectID matches MongoDB's native 12-byte representation. Use it when your application stores `_id` values alongside MongoDB clients or needs to preserve that wire format."],[112,"One install, every ID strategy. Import the generator your application needs."],[21,"Option"],[30,"Option"],[39,"Option"],[48,"Option"],[55,"Option"],[65,"Option"],[72,"Option"],[78,"Option"],[83,"Option"],[93,"Option"],[100,"Option"],[28,"Output as a JSON array instead of one ID per line"],[98,"Output as JSON"],[109,"Output as JSON"],[37,"Output in lowercase"],[46,"Output in lowercase"],[209,"Performance and bundle size"],[272,"Pick an ID format for the job, then import only that generator."],[312,"Prepare for the v1 entry-point contract without changing identifier data."],[126,"Primary value"],[185,"Public API resources"],[172,"Public inputs are validated. Explicit random bytes and buffer offsets make tests and boundary integrations deterministic without changing the generator's default monotonic state."],[329,"Purpose"],[392,"Random, standards-compatible UUIDs with 122 bits of entropy."],[105,"Read IDs from stdin (one per line)"],[335,"Read the reference for the strategy you use. The public method sections are generated from the TypeScript signatures and JSDoc in `packages/uniku/src`, so they stay aligned with the library source."],[319,"Read the stability contract for the full release and runtime policy."],[213,"Reproduce these numbers"],[269,"Run the benchmark and bundle-size tooling from the repository root:"],[167,"See Choosing an ID for the trade-offs, or open a generator reference when you already know which format you need."],[231,"See the current benchmark summary"],[188,"Short URLs and invite codes"],[179,"Situation"],[389,"Sortable, URL-safe identifiers using Crockford Base32."],[271,"Start here"],[123,"Strategy"],[170,"String-native formats do not pretend otherwise. Nanoid and CUID v2 have no canonical byte encoding, so they expose a smaller API."],[333,"The canonical ordered list of supported generator kinds."],[205,"The conventional random UUID format."],[268,"The CUID v2 entry point imports SHA3-512 from `@noble/hashes`, uniku's one runtime dependency; the size above excludes that external dependency's own weight."],[401,"The default identity is random and cached for this runtime. Supplying `machineId` or `processId` changes only that field; calls still use the shared counter unless you also supply `counter`. Supply all four fields for deterministic output."],[317,"The generator behavior is the same. This is an import migration, not a data migration: existing CUID v2 values remain valid."],[273,"The library contract"],[279,"The library is ESM-only, built on web standards, and tested end to end across Node.js, Bun, Deno, browsers, and Cloudflare Workers. Its supported `1.x` entry points, validation boundaries, and runtime support policy are defined in the stability contract."],[214,"The numbers below come from the repository's own benchmark and bundle-size tooling, reproduced faithfully including the rows where an npm alternative wins. They run in CI on every push to `main` (GitHub Actions, `ubuntu-latest`), so they reflect ordinary Node.js execution rather than a tuned environment. See the README for the source table."],[326,"The package root is intentionally not exported. Import a generator or metadata module directly:"],[294,"The rest of `uuid`'s API maps onto uniku's per-generator methods, scoped to the version you imported:"],[324,"The stable direct imports exposed by uniku."],[92,"The type is auto-detected unless `--type` is given. For time-ordered IDs (UUID v7, ULID, TypeID, KSUID, ObjectID, XID, TSID), inspect extracts the embedded timestamp. Random-only IDs (UUID v4, CUID v2, Nanoid) report that no decodable metadata is available. Timestamp precision matches each generator: UUID v7, ULID, and TSID are millisecond-precision; KSUID, ObjectID, and XID are second-precision."],[114,"The usual shape"],[169,"This matters when an ID lives in a binary database column, a compact protocol payload, or a cache key. A UUID, for instance, is 16 bytes instead of its 36-character string form. The helpers also make the string boundary explicit: convert when data leaves your application, preserve bytes where the system already handles bytes."],[355,"Thrown when"],[177,"Time order leaks creation time"],[176,"Time ordering is local"],[121,"Time-ordered formats also expose `timestamp()`. Each generator page lists its complete public API, including options, constants, and overloads."],[373,"Time-ordered identifiers with a 128-bit random payload."],[396,"Time-ordered UUIDs for primary keys, APIs, and event streams."],[184,"Time-ordered values improve index locality."],[383,"Time-sorted 64-bit identifiers for native bigint storage."],[13,"tsid"],[163,"TSID"],[201,"TSID"],[224,"TSID"],[382,"TSID"],[384,"TSID returns a `bigint`, not a string. Use it when a database `BIGINT` primary key is the natural representation and you still need time ordering without a central allocator."],[327,"Two metadata entry points round out the library:"],[53,"Type prefix, e.g. `user` for `user_...` (empty by default)"],[348,"Typed, machine-readable errors for invalid input, malformed strings, and buffer bounds."],[331,"Typed, machine-readable input, parse, and buffer errors."],[7,"typeid"],[139,"TypeID"],[186,"TypeID"],[222,"TypeID"],[385,"TypeID"],[387,"TypeID wraps a UUID v7 suffix in a lowercase prefix such as `user_` or `order_`. It is useful when a public identifier should reveal the kind of resource it identifies."],[6,"ulid"],[135,"ULID"],[218,"ULID"],[388,"ULID"],[390,"ULIDs sort by creation time and stay shorter than a hyphenated UUID. Use them when the value will often appear in URLs, logs, or APIs."],[296,"uniku"],[240,"uniku does not claim a uniform speedup. For UUID v4 and 10-character Nanoid, the npm original is marginally faster; those formats do little work, so there is not much room to gain by reimplementing them."],[118,"uniku is ESM-only. Import the exact generator you want rather than a package-root barrel:"],[293,"uniku only generates UUID v4 and v7. There is no uniku equivalent for v1, v3, v5, or v6; keep the `uuid` package for those, or generate them elsewhere and only use uniku for v4 and v7 values."],[315,"uniku v1 keeps its public generator entry points stable and removes one pre-v1 compatibility alias."],[217,"uniku vs npm"],[44,"Unix timestamp in milliseconds, or `now`"],[86,"Unix timestamp in milliseconds, or `now`"],[75,"Unix timestamp in seconds, or `now`"],[81,"Unix timestamp in seconds, or `now`"],[110,"Use `--json` whenever the output feeds another program. The CLI and library publish independently: a library `1.0.0` release does not imply a CLI `1.0.0` release at the same time."],[394,"Use `toBytes()` when the destination stores UUIDs as 16-byte binary values. Use `isValid()` before accepting an unknown UUID v4 string at an application boundary."],[309,"Use `xid.toBytes(id)` and `xid.fromBytes(bytes)` when you store the 12-byte value."],[125,"Usual call"],[5,"uuid"],[127,"UUID v4"],[204,"UUID v4"],[238,"UUID v4"],[391,"UUID v4"],[393,"UUID v4 is the default when compatibility matters more than sort order. It fits databases and APIs that already understand UUID strings."],[131,"UUID v7"],[232,"UUID v7"],[395,"UUID v7"],[386,"UUID v7 identifiers with a readable, domain-specific prefix."],[397,"UUID v7 keeps the UUID shape while embedding a millisecond timestamp. It is a strong default for database primary keys when you want chronological locality without creating a custom ID column."],[183,"UUID v7 or ULID"],[187,"UUID v7 with a readable, domain-specific prefix."],[208,"UUID v7, ULID, KSUID, ObjectID, XID, and TSID embed a creation timestamp in the identifier itself. Anyone who can read the ID can decode when the record was created, not just its order relative to other records. That is a feature for index locality and a leak if the ID is public and the creation time is sensitive, for example a document, invoice, or account that should not reveal how old it is. If the identifier is exposed outside your system and creation time must stay private, use UUID v4, CUID v2, or Nanoid instead: none of them encode a timestamp."],[207,"UUID v7, ULID, ObjectID, XID, and TSID carry time information. uniku keeps the state required for monotonic sequencing inside one JavaScript isolate; it does not coordinate clocks or sequences between processes or machines."],[35,"UUID version: `4` or `7` (default: `4`)"],[168,"UUIDs, ULIDs, TypeIDs, KSUIDs, ObjectIDs, XIDs, and TSIDs have a canonical binary representation. Their `toBytes()` and `fromBytes()` helpers let you store and transport that representation without inventing a second codec."],[15,"Validate"],[191,"Values that should resist enumeration"],[314,"What remains stable"],[210,"Where uniku beats npm alternatives, where it does not, and what each import weighs."],[181,"Why"],[116,"Why byte helpers exist"],[318,"Within `1.x`, uniku will not remove or rename documented entry points, exports, options, methods, or constants. Canonical string formats, byte order, timestamp units, and documented error codes are part of the contract."],[117,"Write into a caller-owned buffer"],[12,"xid"],[159,"XID"],[198,"XID"],[230,"XID"],[398,"XID"],[400,"XID is a 12-byte, lowercase base32hex identifier: a seconds-precision timestamp, a 40-bit per-runtime identity, and a shared 24-bit counter. Use it when you need Go's rs/xid wire format in a synchronous JavaScript runtime."]],"type":"string"},"page_id":{"docs":{"1":10,"2":11,"3":12,"4":13,"5":14,"6":15,"7":16,"8":17,"9":18,"10":19,"11":20,"12":21,"13":22,"14":23,"15":24,"16":25,"17":26,"18":27,"19":28,"20":29,"21":30,"22":31,"23":32,"24":33,"25":34,"26":35,"27":36,"28":37,"29":38,"30":39,"31":40,"32":41,"33":42,"34":43,"35":44,"36":45,"37":46,"38":47,"39":48,"40":49,"41":50,"42":51,"43":52,"44":53,"45":54,"46":55,"47":56,"48":57,"49":58,"50":59,"51":60,"52":61,"53":62,"54":63,"55":64,"56":65,"57":66,"58":67,"59":68,"60":69,"61":70,"62":71,"63":72,"64":73,"65":74,"66":75,"67":76,"68":77,"69":78,"70":79,"71":80,"72":81,"73":82,"74":83,"75":84,"76":85,"77":86,"78":87,"79":88,"80":89,"81":90,"82":91,"83":92,"84":93,"85":94,"86":95,"87":96,"88":97,"89":98,"90":99,"91":100,"92":101,"93":102,"94":103,"95":104,"96":105,"97":106,"98":107,"99":108,"100":109,"101":110,"102":111,"103":112,"104":113,"105":114,"106":115,"107":116,"108":117,"109":118,"110":119,"111":120,"112":121,"113":122,"114":123,"115":124,"116"